WEBVTT

00:00.100 --> 00:02.620
Okay, let's talk about key really quick.

00:02.620 --> 00:05.920
Key is here.

00:05.920 --> 00:07.240
It seems kind of strange.

00:07.240 --> 00:08.960
Let's just delete it here for a second.

00:08.960 --> 00:10.760
Is this actually, oh yeah.

00:10.760 --> 00:13.800
Good for you, React, for remembering to tell me that.

00:14.940 --> 00:16.840
But it's gonna yell at you here in the console as well.

00:16.840 --> 00:18.220
It says that each thing should have a unique key.

00:18.220 --> 00:21.220
Probably seen that several times throughout the course here.

00:21.220 --> 00:23.080
What is this all about?

00:23.080 --> 00:25.560
All right, imagine you have

00:25.560 --> 00:28.220
extremely complicated components, right?

00:28.220 --> 00:30.300
And they render a bunch of images

00:30.300 --> 00:32.220
and text and stuff like that.

00:32.220 --> 00:34.180
And then the user refilters,

00:34.180 --> 00:36.860
and it just swaps like two components.

00:36.860 --> 00:38.900
Like what was here is now down here,

00:38.900 --> 00:40.700
and what is here is now up here.

00:40.700 --> 00:42.580
React doesn't have a concept of like

00:42.580 --> 00:44.020
what was here and what was where.

00:44.020 --> 00:46.100
And so what it's gonna do is it's going to tear down

00:46.100 --> 00:49.500
everything and rebuild everything from the ground up again.

00:50.620 --> 00:52.500
Sometimes that's okay.

00:53.460 --> 00:55.620
Sometimes it's not okay.

00:55.620 --> 00:57.740
What key does when you're doing like these kind of like

00:57.740 --> 00:59.780
map sort of things like we're doing here,

00:59.780 --> 01:02.280
and there's a lot of peer components next to each other,

01:02.280 --> 01:04.060
that could be rearranged.

01:05.220 --> 01:07.820
We don't rearrange these, but in theory we could.

01:10.140 --> 01:13.860
What key does is saying like here is a unique thing

01:13.860 --> 01:15.800
that's tied to this object.

01:16.780 --> 01:20.100
So like what's unique to a pizza, it's ID, right?

01:20.100 --> 01:22.220
And so that way if we swap two things, it's like,

01:22.220 --> 01:25.100
oh, you had this here and now you have it here

01:25.100 --> 01:27.940
because I have this like identifier that I can look at

01:27.940 --> 01:30.180
to see like this move from here to here.

01:30.180 --> 01:31.660
I'm just gonna swap the components

01:31.660 --> 01:34.620
as opposed to tearing everything down and rebuilding it.

01:34.620 --> 01:36.020
Right, does that make sense?

01:37.000 --> 01:39.060
So that's why it just yells at you constantly

01:39.060 --> 01:40.500
like please put a key on here.

01:40.500 --> 01:42.920
It's just a habit you wanna get into.

01:42.920 --> 01:46.080
I will say here is a very common misstep here.

01:47.780 --> 01:49.600
What happens if I grab the index?

01:50.600 --> 01:52.640
Why is this not okay?

01:54.720 --> 01:56.000
It's not stable.

01:56.000 --> 01:57.320
It's not tied to the object,

01:57.320 --> 01:59.080
which I think is what you're getting at, right?

01:59.080 --> 02:04.080
So if I move pepperoni from index zero to index five,

02:04.760 --> 02:07.320
pepperoni and zero weren't associated,

02:07.320 --> 02:10.520
so it's gonna think that as like, oh, okay,

02:10.520 --> 02:12.920
pepperoni or five stayed in the same place,

02:12.920 --> 02:13.760
so I'm not gonna change anything.

02:13.760 --> 02:16.320
And it actually did change, right?

02:16.880 --> 02:19.160
So that's why you can't do it that way

02:19.160 --> 02:23.160
because the index and the object are not tied to each other.

02:23.160 --> 02:25.920
There's no relation between those two things.

02:26.880 --> 02:28.280
That being said, there's sometimes,

02:28.280 --> 02:31.160
there's just not a key to associate with something.

02:31.160 --> 02:34.840
Sometimes it just doesn't matter if it gets reorganized.

02:34.840 --> 02:36.320
So you'll find me doing this sometimes

02:36.320 --> 02:37.920
where I just want the linter to shut up

02:37.920 --> 02:39.680
and get out of my way, right?

02:39.680 --> 02:43.320
You can do this this way and put the index there.

02:43.320 --> 02:47.480
So I'm gonna do this this way and put the index there.

